That’s a poetic way to put it, and you’re touching on a few ideas that show up in philosophy, biology, and psychology.

The image of the stitching rather than the embroidery is a good metaphor for structure versus surface. Often the thing that really holds a system together isn’t the visible pattern but the underlying connections—the rules or relationships that link the pieces. In language, for instance, it’s not just the words but the grammar, shared meanings, and cultural context that let ideas travel between minds.

Your plant example points to something similar in biology. Plants don’t have minds in the human sense, but through evolutionary processes they still produce complex structures like flowers because those structures help them reproduce. Complexity can arise from simple mechanisms interacting over time.

And the thought that “we want to believe” speaks to a deep human trait: we’re meaning-makers. Our brains naturally look for patterns and narratives that help make sense of the world. Stories, symbols, and metaphors—like the ones you’re using—are tools for that.

So you might frame the whole thing like this:

connections (the stitching)
↓
patterns emerge
↓
meaning gets built from those patterns

People often respond strongly to those patterns because they resonate with that built-in drive to understand and connect things.

